Hi @jeremydubreil yes that's a good point.  My example was contrived; I wanted to keep things simple to make sure I was running the tool correctly.  Probably the right thing to do is to assume usage similar to Guava when annotations from class files are being parsed.  If it's clearly documented, I think that would work well for most cases.  Also, maybe the default should be to behave just as Infer does now (ignoring annotations in class files) to avoid surprises and/or a ton of unwanted false positives.

@sblackshear, it would actually be easy to load the annotations from the 3rd party library. There is already some support for analyzing the dependencies. For example (changing the example a bit to avoid the issue with `@NonNull` mentioned earlier):


and

We can actually have Eradicate report the issue using the undocumented `--dependencies` options:

The reason why we don't use `--dependencies` by default is to avoid duplication of work when using Buck as the same class. e.g. `java.lang.String` could otherwise be analyzed on many different Buck targets.

The new genrule based approach to integrate Infer with Buck could actually allow use to analyze the third party libraries only once (decorating `prebuilt_jar`) and cache the analysis artifacts, which would contain the annotations as well. cc @kageiit

@jeremydubreil That sounds like a great idea. As long as infer knows how to extract the analysis artifacts from the `prebuilt_jar` or `prebuilt_android_aar` decorated infer/eradicate genrules, the performance impact will be minimal and the quality of analysis will be a lot greater. Seems like that is the best approach forward.

Like @jvillard, I think it will be hard to tell without seeing more code, but here's a few ideas off the top of my head:

- Try running infer with `--no-filtering`
- Report on the `proc_name`/ `proc_desc`/`location` of the current procedure rather using `e.proc_desc` and so on. I think all of the checkers we have so far log errors that occur in a function `foo` called from `main` in `main` rather than in `foo` (we have a mechanism for displaying interprocedural traces that will show the path from `main` to `foo`). In principle, reporting the error from anywhere should work, but I haven't tried it.

@cristianoc's advice about disabling the the other checkers is also very important. I forgot to mention this in the documentation, but there's a limitation where we can only register one interprocedural checker at a time (otherwise, they clobber each other's results).

Hello @xennygrimmato,
To use `L.err`/`L.out` you have to be in developer mode, which means you need to invoke infer with the `--developer-mode` argument (as you can see [here](https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/fe780cb6ffd236cf618c2f9b63b03ddd2de18764/infer/src/backend/logging.ml#L142-L148))

But even if you use that, there may be many different processes running one after the other during the analysis thus overwriting the content of the `analyzer_err` and `analyzer_out` log files, and this should explain why they look empty at the end.

For now, try using `L.stdout`/`L.stderr` to get your output in the console, and you don't need to run in developer mode to use it.

@brotherpaul143 it seems that Infer and SATE use two opposite definitions of correct/sound. From your website:

"1. The tool is claimed to be sound."

and

"Sound means every finding is correct. The tool need not produce a finding for every site; that is completeness."

This is simply not the case for Infer: reports made by Infer may not correspond to an actual weakness in the code.

Note that Infer is sound in the logical sense, which seems to correspond to your notion of "completeness": if Infer doesn't report on a procedure, then that procedure has no bugs (as @jberdine said, "subject to some idealistic and optimistic assumptions"). Infer reports a bug when it fails to prove that a procedure has no bugs (and when Infer's internal heuristics suggest that it may correspond to a real issue, otherwise Infer would be too noisy), not when it can prove that a procedure definitely has a bug.

I agree with you, @jvillard   Please note that Ockham uses the term "finding". The use of "finding" allows an additional level of interpretation. As you point out, "if Infer doesn't report on a procedure, then that procedure has no bugs". The _lack_ of a report is a finding for Ockham's purposes. That is, users can absolutely depend on the fact that no bug reportfrom Infer  means that the procedure is bug-free "subject to some idealistic and optimistic assumptions", as @jberdine said.

Infer is welcome to participate in Ockham.

@jvillard -- Sorry for the delay. Appreciate all the activity in this thread.

To analyze my project, I was just using the recommended flow: `infer -- ./gradlew assembleDebug`.

With Retrolambda in the mix, the Android build process is something like:
- Run `javac` over your source files to produce Java 8 bytecode.
- Retrolambda transforms the bytecode to be Java 6/7 compatible.
- `dx` transforms the transformed bytecode into a `.dex` file.

I believe that Infer relies on the `javac` output from the gradle build process (please correct me if I'm mistaken--certainly no expert here), so maybe the issue is that it's using the pre-transformed bytecode.

(I'll try to put together a minimal example.)

Two quick asides, though:
1. It's unclear to me if this is worth fixing right now, since I imagine that a lot will have to change with the introduction of [Jack](http://developer.android.com/preview/j8-jack.html) (already available in the N developer preview), which will make some Java 8 language features standard in Android (backwards compatible to Gingerbread) and will remove the `javac` step from the Android build process.
2. Not relevant to this particular issue, but... it's interesting to me that Infer operates on bytecode, yet it ties in so well with annotations, which (I believe?) are stripped out by the time you get to bytecode (again, please correct me if I'm wrong). Are there any resources around for learning more about how that works?
Thanks for looking into this, @kstreee! We'll be pushing further improvements to that part of the code soon as well.

@tonycosentini: Unfortunately, you cannot use Infer and Eradicate using the same out directory because the analysis data are not compatible. This is not a theoretical limitation but it will require a good amount of changes to support this use case. Is it possible in your setting to just make a copy of `infer-out` after `infer -a capture` and before running the analysis ?

Besides, I think that the `-i` option is not compatible with running the analysis in two steps using:

  `infer -a capture --`

followed by:

  `infer -- analyze`

Is the approach or running:

  `infer -i -a eradicate -o eradicate-out -- ...`

and independently:

  `infer -i -a infer -o infer-out -- ...`

blocking for you ?

Hi @tonycosentini. There is no easy support for that right now. The filtering is implemented in this file: https://github.com/facebook/infer/blob/master/infer/lib/python/inferlib/issues.py#L259

However, the `RETURN_VALUE_IGNORED` should be displayed by default. I am not sure we actually ever looked at how this check for return values behaves in Java. Are you using Infer with the `--no-filtering` option ?

Hello @emkou,
As @jvillard said, `NSUserDefaults+App.h` doesn't look like a system header, so I'd proceed as he suggested, by passing to Clang the path where this file lives, using the `-I` argument.

More in general, when `xcodebuild` builds each file of your codebase, it passes to Clang more arguments than just the source filename, and among those there's the `-isysroot` one, which tells Clang where your SDK lives.
For example, your iPhoneSimulator SDK should be located in:



try passing `-isysroot <SDK_PATH>` to your Clang command.

Hey @Elmundo, @martinoluca, I had the same issue...
Reinstalling command line tools has fixed it for me. 
I'm running OSX 10.11 (15A178w), and command line tools for Xcode 6.3.2. 
Xcode 7 beta command line tools break this in a completely different way for me.

Workaround
--- 

### Generate a json compilation database
If you add the [following parameter](http://oclint-docs.readthedocs.io/en/stable/guide/xctool.html#running-xctool-with-json-compilation-database-reporter) to 
* `xctool`: `-reporter json-compilation-database:compile_commands.json` 
* `xcpretty`:  `-r json-compilation-database -o compile_commands.json`

#### This'll enable you to use one of the following commands: 
Depending on how you generate this file you use one of the following options:
*  `xcpretty` and `xctool`: `--clang-compilation-db-files-escaped` 
    * reason: the files in the json are escaped : 'file\\ with\\ spaces'
* `cmake`: `--clang-compilation-db-files`

Granted, it'd be a 2 step process, but it'll work ðŸ‘ 

**NB** Commonly, the build output will be stored in a file called 'xcodebuild.log'. If you need a different reporter for e.g. your test, you can still do that, generate the `compile_commands.json` using that log file, and launch infer using that generated `compile_commands.json`

Concretely:
1. `xctool.sh --<whatever parameters you need> -reporter json-compilation-database:compile_commands.json` or `xcodebuild --<whatever parameters> | tee xcodebuild.log | xcpretty -r junit -o junit.xml` as usual
2. `cat xcodebuild.log | xcpretty -r json-compilation-database -o compile_commands.json &> /dev/null`
    * the last part pipes the output  to `/dev/null`, as otherwise it'd be displayed on screen again, convoluting your build log.
3. `infer --skip-analysis-in-path Pods --clang-compilation-db-files-escaped compile_commands.json`

Strictly speaking, it's true that the code will not generate an NPE. That said, the choice Infer makes is to report anyway. If a project deliberately catches `NullPointerException`, Infer will produce a lot of unintended reports. For such projects (if they exist), a different message would help.

I suspect that it would be hard to implement that behaviour in infer: if `foo()` dereferences null, then infer will want to report on `foo()`. But maybe `foo()` is only called from inside `bar()`, which catches `Exception` or `NullPointerException`. Currently, infer has no way to know every context in which `foo()` is called prior to analysing `foo()`, so it would be hard to avoid reporting on `foo()`.

That said, as @martinoluca was saying in #422, such code patterns are dubious at best anyway.
